Fukushima and the collapse of derivatives
CAMBRIDGE – Financial commentators have equated the earthquakes, tsunami and nuclear disaster in Japan to the role of derivatives in the 2008 financial crisis.
The similarity is quite clear: each of these activities generates huge profits and involves a very low but explosive risk.
Yet, the similarity between the two types of crisis ends where the way to prevent their reoccurrence begins.
In the case of the Fukushima nuclear plant, a once-in-a-century flood, combined with usually harmless design flaws, caused the stoppage of cooling water circulation in the reactors and significant radiation leaks.
In terms of financial markets, an unexpected collapse of real estate values, combined with design flaws in derivative and repo markets, damaged the ability of major financial institutions to honor their debts.
Although the basic risks originate outside the systems – a tsunami for Fukushima, over-investment in mortgage loans for financial institutions – design flaws and a lack of luck made it so that the systems could not contain the damage.
In the United States, AIG, Bear Stearns, and Lehman Brothers – all with significant investments in derivatives and/or repos – collapsed, causing a freeze in credit on the markets for several long weeks.
We now understand fairly well the risks and design flaws of Fukushima.
We cannot say the same about the risks of derivatives that shook the global economy.
A Fukushima, the teams of workers are bravely trying to stop the radiation leaks.
On the other hand, for the derivatives, similar efforts are misdirected and will not allow us to avoid the next financial crisis.
We are recreating derivatives and similar financial structures, on top of the same errors that are still active.
Financial actors use financial products to transfer risk: for example, an actor accepts the risk of the euro's fluctuation but does not want the risk on the yen, whereas for another, it will be the opposite.
In this case, the first promises to provide euros on June 1st, and the second promises to provide yens.
If a currency loses value compared to the other, the loser pays the difference.
Repos are financial transactions.
Financial firms sell assets, such as Treasury bills or mortgage debt, for cash and promise to repurchase these assets later, typically the next day (hence the name "repo," which is an abbreviation for the English verb repurchase – or to buy back, note).
The problem is that the cash from these short-term repos represents a large part of the balance sheets of the most important financial institutions, which implies that even minor financial tremors can affect them significantly.
Some institutions may then find themselves without repo financing, as in 2008, and go bankrupt, as Bear Stearns did.
Individually considered, transactions on derivatives or repos are not particularly blameworthy.
Each separately legitimately transfers risk to those better able to bear it, or allows for financial participation.
However, when used excessively by institutions that are vital at the systemic level, they can cause the financial system to collapse, due to its design flaws.
Even today, approximately 70% of the liabilities of major US financial institutions consist of very short-term loans, such as repos payable the next day.
In the United States, the main design flaws lie in bankruptcy legislation, which exempts derivatives and repos from most usual constraints in the event of bankruptcy.
For example, investors who hold derivative contracts or repos with financially weakened institutions can seize the company's assets before – and at the expense of – its normal creditors. In doing so, they can decide its fate, whereas, with a little more time, the company in question could have survived.
Such actions ruined AIG, Bear Stearns and others during the financial crisis.
Worse still, because investors in derivatives and repos find themselves at the front of the repayment line in so many ways, they have less incentive to encourage market discipline by closely examining the solvency of their counterparties and by carefully rationing their exposure to any single counterparty.
Typically, they will be repaid, regardless.
Of course, someone must be first.
D’autres acteurs financiers doivent supporter plus de risque du fait que les exemptions des acteurs en produits dérivés et repo placent ces derniers en première ligne en cas de faillite.
Normalement, on s’attendrait à ce que les autres aient donc un intérêt à encourager davantage de discipline de marché.
Mais l’acteur qui suit dans la ligne est trop souvent le gouvernement américain, en tant que garant d’institutions financières « too-big-to-fail » (trop importantes pour les laisser faire faillite, ndt). Or, le gouvernement est mal placé pour réguler ces marchés au quotidien.
Il n’est pas agile financièrement ; il se cantonne souvent au marché régulé ; et, lorsque les conditions économiques sont bonnes, aucun officiel ne voudrait gâcher la fête.
Le Congrès américain a eu une opportunité de solutionner ce défaut dans le remaniement majeur de la finance qu’il a adopté l’été dernier via le projet de loi Dodd Frank.
But he did not seize it.
If derivatives investors, repos and credit-default swaps (credit event derivatives, note) did not benefit from favorable treatment, they would behave differently.
First and foremost, they would more often insist that their counterparties be adequately capitalized.
They accepted the risk generated by extremely low capitalizations when it was essentially U.S. government money; they would be less inclined to do so if it were their own money they were risking.
The public perceives risks of the Fukushima type differently from risks associated with derivatives.
Many people fear nuclear risks, which are striking, causing a slowdown in the sector that must deal with security concerns.
However, the markets for derivatives and repos present risks that are poorly understood, difficult to communicate in the media, and complicated to discuss and resolve for politicians.
During a crisis, these markets attract the attention and contempt of the public, but when the economy stabilizes again, ordinary people lose all interest, leaving the financial sector to control its own destiny with the legislative body.
Regarding risks of the Fukushima type, analysts are already discussing how nuclear plants can be designed and built to contain risks related to earthquakes and tsunamis through passive cooling systems.
It is now considered possible to design nuclear plants capable of maintaining cold fuel rods even in the event of a complete power outage.
On the contrary, few significant progress has been made so far in order to prevent the damage that the priority of derivatives and repos in case of failure could generate during a new financial system crisis.
New rules are being developed, which require that end-users (such as oil companies using derivatives to protect against unanticipated price changes of oil) and others post high-quality collateral.
However, these rules do not address the main problem: the weak incentives for market discipline for the major financial institutions.
It's as if we were reacting to Fukushima by better controlling gas emissions in oil extraction projects.
We should examine how to fully let investors in derivatives and repos bear the risk associated with their decisions when they carry out transactions with financial institutions that are systemically important.
Instead of that, we survived the 2008 financial tsunami only to rebuild in the same place, with the same financial flaws and according to the same defective design.
